&gt; I&#39;m using heritrix version 1.14.4. Initially when the crawl started it
&gt; started with congestion ratio of 1 to 1.45 but after some time the
&gt; congestion ratio went up to 2.5 max

The &#39;congestion ratio&#39; is (very roughly) an multiple suggesting how many 
more ToeThreads, of equivalent capability as those that exist, would 
mean that at this moment no queues would be waiting for a thread.

So when it&#39;s 1, and especially when the number of active threads is less 
than the configured maximum, that suggests the limiting factor is 
politeness/retry delays and the sites themselves, not local machine 
resources.

Your previous progress-statistics log definitely showed that situation 
for its very slow crawl-rates.

These latest log excerpts are different, and I&#39;m not even sure the lines 
you have from 7/08 are from the same JVM-launch and crawl as 7/13 
(usually the heap size doesn&#39;t go down).

&gt; the ratio of Queued:Downloaded is 7:1 which indicates that there are so
&gt; many inactive-queues even if there are as many (as 500 busy threads) ?
&gt; where are the threads spending their time ?

The ratio of queued:downloaded isn&#39;t really significant. The overall 
magnitude of queued gives a general idea of the size of the queues and 
alreadyIncluded structures, which can be a drag on large crawls (as more 
IO is required for URI seen-checking and insertion). Often for crawls we 
expect to grow beyond a few tens of millions of URIs we swap out the 
default BdbUriUniqFilter with an all-RAM BloomFilter-based 
implementation, accepting a small risk of false positives (believing an 
URL was collected when it wasn&#39;t) for zero-IO lookups.

That may be a contributing factor in your latest slowdowns, showing a 
less than 2GB heap and over 75million discovered URIs. Especially if new 
pages found are very diverse-outlink-heavy, checking every one against 
the 77-million-URI alreadyIncluded, which is mostly on disk, is a 
typical crawl bottleneck.

Also any swapping at all can easily cause a massive slowdown.

The best way to take a snapshot of where threads are at a certain moment 
is the web UI&#39;s &#39;Threads Report&#39; (for all ToeThreads) or the JVM&#39;s 
thread dump (via -SIGQUIT or the &#39;jstack&#39; tool). Often the patterns here 
indicate what bottlenecks could be removed short of other optimizations.

&gt; BTW i&#39;m using a ParallelQueue that i implemented and not the
&gt; HostQueueAssignmentPolicy. Even with using HostQueueAssignmentPolicy i
&gt; dont get enough throughput and i don&#39;t care about politeness at this
&gt; point since I&#39;m using it for crawling our own site.

A custom parallel-queuing approach could potentially go astray and cause 
problems, especially with regard to the handling of necessary 
prerequisite URIs (DNS, robots).

- Gordon @ IA

